<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-402-144  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 402 144.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  April 30 1990 v7 n17 p35(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>New chip set may fuel FDDI growth. (National Semiconductor Inc.;andO;Fiber Distributed Data Interface)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Higgins, Steve.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>National Semiconductor Inc introduces a new chip set that thecompany hopes will quicken the spread of high-speed fiber-opticnetworks.andP;  The chip set is based on the Fiber Distributed DataInterface (FDDI) specification, one of the few chip sets thatconforms to the 100M-bps FDDI standard.andP;  The product makes FDDImore competitive, pushing down the cost of installing FDDInetworks by increasing the availability of chips and efficiency ofFDDI adapters.andP;  The chip set will also encourage vendors toinclude as standard, FDDI networking capabilities in high-endgraphics workstations.andP;  The product incorporates a processor thatfilters FDDI data, eliminating the need to augment an FDDI adapterwith an on-board processor.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   National Semiconductor Corp. (product introduction).andO;Ticker:    NSM.andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionChip SetsConnectivityFiber Distributed Data Interface Standard.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   The shrinking cost of adding fiber to your connectivity diet.andO;(graph)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Steve HigginsandM;National Semiconductor Inc. this week hopes to hasten the spread ofhigh-speed fiber-optic networks with the introduction of a new chip set basedon the Fiber Distributed Data Interface (FDDI) specification.andM;With the five-chip set, National Semiconductor joins Advanced Micro DevicesInc. as the only firms to provide chips for developing products that conformto the 100M-bps FDDI standard.andM;The chip set, which is expected to spawn end-user fiber-optic products asearly as June, should push down the cost of installing FDDI networks byincreasing both the efficiency of FDDI adapters and the availability of chipson which such products are based, according to company officials andobservers.andM;&quot;The National chip set makes FDDI more competitive,&quot; said Rick Villars,manager of computer networking systems for International Data Corp., amarket-research firm in Framingham, Mass.andP;  &quot;It puts pressure on allmanufacturers [of FDDI products] to be more competitive.&quot;andM;In addition to the potential cost savings, the new chip set is also designedto encourage vendors to include FDDI networking capabilities as a standardcomponent of high-end graphics workstations, company officials said.andM;The chip set incorporates a special processor designed to filter FDDI data,eliminating the need to augment an FDDI adapter with an on-board processor,according to Karen Parker, strategic program manager for NationalSemiconductor in Santa Clara, Calif.andP;  Such a design could also allowmanufacturers to add the chip set directly to a workstation's motherboard,she said.andM;However, users will first see the chip set used in an add-in adapter fromNetwork Peripherals Inc.andM;The San Jose, Calif., company plans to ship in June a pair of add-in cardsdesigned to link AT-compatible workstations to FDDI networks, companyofficials said.andM;The $3,495 NP-ISA/S will let users connect an AT workstation to a single FDDInetwork cable.andP;  The $7,000 NP-ISA/D will exploit the ability of FDDI networksto support redundant links, letting the workstation link to two FDDI cablesof the same network, said Darrell Scherbath, vice president of engineering atNetwork Peripherals.andM;National Semiconductor is also offering an evaluation kit for its new chipset.andP;  The $6,000 kit comprises a pair of FDDI adapters based on the chips andsoftware for testing the chips' ability to exploit FDDI network-managementfeatures.andM;National Semiconductor can be reached at (408) 721-4960.andP;  Network Peripheralscan be reached at (408) 954-8030.andO;</TEXT></DOC>